# Git Rules

## Branch Naming (Mandatory)

Feature → feat-name-of-what-you-did  
Fix → fix-name-of-what-you-did  
Chore → chore-name-of-what-you-did  

Rules:
- Use kebab-case.
- No uppercase letters.
- No spaces.
- Name must clearly describe the change.
- AI must suggest the branch name before starting any task.

Example:
feat-login-system  
fix-timer-memory-leak  
chore-refactor-utils  

---

## Commit Messages — Conventional Commits (Mandatory)

All commits must follow:

type(scope): short-description

Example:
feat(auth): add login validation  
fix(timer): resolve interval duplication  
chore(utils): refactor date helpers  
...
---

### Allowed Types

feat      → new feature  
fix       → bug fix  
chore     → maintenance  
refactor  → internal restructuring  
docs      → documentation only  
style     → formatting only (no logic changes)  
test      → tests added/updated  
perf      → performance improvements  
build     → build/dependency changes  
ci        → CI configuration changes  

---

### Rules

- Subject must be lowercase.
- Use imperative mood (add, fix, update — not added, fixed).
- No trailing period.
- Keep subject under 72 characters.
- One logical change per commit.

---

### Breaking Changes

If introducing breaking changes:

feat(auth)!: change login response format

OR

feat(auth): change login response format

BREAKING CHANGE: login now returns user object instead of token